Horace never speaks from the plat· form, or with any assumption of superior virtue ς he talks as one of the crowd who has stopped to reflect on their common weaknesses, and he disarms resentment by sometimes turn- ing the laugh against himself. There are some who esteem these ‘talks' (summes), as he himself preferred to call thern, the greatest of Horace’s achievements. Certainly there are few works of classical antiquity in which literary art has brought us so near to ancient life.
